description:
Getting in the newspaper comic strip game at the age of 14 Charles A. Voight was one of the early creators of the form, his best known newspaper strip being Betty, one of the first glamour-girl strips. 
 
In the mid 40s she started working for the comics creating such characters as the golden-age Immpossible Man, and Captain Milksop, with his longest running character being Boom Boom Brannigan in Prize Comics.

deck: Artist of Nathan Never, comic of Sergio Bonelli Editore.
description:
Stefano Casini was born June 3, 1958, in Livorno. 
He attended the Academy of Arts-Free Rosignano, and later enrolled at I.S.I.A. High School of Industrial Design in Florence.
He works in Italy for several years in the fashion world and for companies of various types, while maintaining a parallel passion for comics.
Finally in 1988 he was selected as an artist for the editor Sergio Bonelli, for whom he continues to draw many stories of Nathan Never.
name: Stefano Casini

deck: The creator of the Criminal Parker.  He is one of the most respected Heist writers and his books are being adapted by Darwyn Cooke.
description:
Best known under the name Richard Stark because of the Parker novels.  Donald E. Westlake would have many pen names: John B. Allan, Judson Jack Carmichael, Curt Clark, Timothy J. Culver, J. Morgan Cunningham, Edwin West, among others 
 
Parker would be a property very special to him, in which all adaptations besides The Darwyn Cooke's Graphic Novels could not actually call the character "Parker".  Cooke and Westlake worked to create an adaption Westlake was happy enough with that could bare the name Parker.  Westlake would die December 31, 2008 at the age of 75 in Mexico.  Westlake would die before he could see his creation Parker adapted into the medium known as comics.
name: Richard Stark (Donald E. Westlake)

deck: An American comic book artist and colorist.
description:
After earning his BFA Degree in Graphic Design from the University of Wisconsin-Stout, Mitch Gerads worked in the packaging design industry for four years where he illustrated for such brands as Cookie Crisp, Trix, Lucky Charms, Cheerios, Teddy Grahams, and many more. Mitch is the co-creator (with Scott Dillon) of Johnny Recon, a comic he illustrated.

Mitch has recently been coloring comics for Boom! Studios and is hard at work drawing The Activity, a new comic written by Nathan Edmondson. He is also a regular contributor to the Comic Twart art blog.
name: Mitch Gerads
